                                                               Rev. 1

                        Regression/Unit Testing Framework
                      =====================================


QUICKSTART
----------

If you want to write a test for some new functionality, say in blancmange.c,
create a new file, blancmange_test.c. It should inherit TEST_CASE.

Now, for each function you wish to test in blancmange.c, create a corresponding
void testFunc() function in blancmange_test.c. This test should exercise
the functionality of Func() in blancmange.c. Use the assert functions in
the TEST_CASE inheritable to test things easily, or you can just use
raise_error. The assert functions, however, do lots of nice formatting of
the results. 

Example:

#include <mudlib.h>
inherit TEST_CASE;

object moMyTestObject;

void setup() { moMyTestObject = clone_object("/players/malraux/blancmange"); }
void teardown() { destruct(moMyTestObject); }

void testFoo()
{
  moMyTestObject->foo();
  assertTrue("testing query_foo", moMyTestObject->query_foo());
}

void testBlah()
{
  moMyTestObject->blah("garble");
  assertEquals("testing query_blah", "garble", moMyTestObject->query_blah());
}  


If you have some state that needs to be set up before each test function
is called, like creating an object, or putting a value into a daemon, then
put those calls into the void setup() function in blancmange_test.c. Make
sure that any objects you create (either in setup() or in a testFunc()) are
explicitly destructed in the void teardown() function, which will get run
after each test function is called.

When you are ready to run your tests, do 'rtest blancmange_test'.

The basic call sequence of rtest is:

 1) load the blancmange_test object.
 2) for each testFoo() function in blancmange_test, do the following:
2a) call setup()
2b) call testFoo()
2c) call teardown()
 3) repeat for each testFoo() function.


Introduction:
------------

Testing frameworks increase the stability and quality of code by ensuring
two things:

Unit testing ensures that code performs as intended.
Regression testing ensures that code *still* performs as intended after
changes are made that could impact the tested code.

In order to make testing easy, Kent Beck designed an object oriented
testing framework that automated the process of creating and running
unit and regression tests. This framework has since been ported to
dozens of languages, including (now, that is) LPC.

Testing enables us not only to make changes without breaking other
pieces of code (provided the tests are run after the changes), but
also to develop more quickly. This may seem counter-intuitive at first,
but consider that you always (or should always) test what you have
coded to make sure it does wha tyou think it does. This usually 
involves the creation of adhoc test scripts or programs. Now, by using
a pre-built testing framework, you can formalize your adhoc testing
so that it can easily be rerun later.


Concepts
--------

#include <mudlib.h> to get the inheritable #defines referenced.

A "test case" is an object that contains a series of test functions,
each of which tests a limited piece of the code being tested.

A "test suite" is a group of test cases.

A "test runner" is an object that knows how to run a suite of tests.
TEST_RUNNER is our implementation of a test runner, and it is 
invoked by the "rtest" command. To run a test case file, do
'rtest </path/to/filetest>'.

Test cases should inherit TEST_CASE, which includes both the
underlying test functionality, as well as a series of assert 
functions that allow you to make determinations about the results
of your tests.

A test case can either contain its own test functions, or it can
merely be a convenience container for a suite of other test case
objects.

When a test case is run, each function in the object beginning
with the word "test" will be run in order. If any errors are 
raised, or any of the calls to assert* functions fail, the test
function will be considered a failure.

Naming consistency: for unit tests that test a paricular .c file,
PLEASE name your tests the same name as the object they are testing
with '_test' appended. This will allow us to write extra functionality
in the update command to automatically run unit tests if they exist.

Example: /inherits/events_test.c


Basic Functionality
-------------------

The test case inheritable defines a reset(int arg) function that
must be called with ::reset(arg) if you override it. The reset
function sets up a number of internal variables.

void setup()
-- This function will be called before each test function in the
   object. Use this to set up data/state in the test that needs
   to be consistent for each test function.

void teardown()
-- This function will be called after each test function in the
   object. Use this to destruct any objects that may have been
   created during the course of the tests.

string *getTests()
-- The function should return an array of function names to call
   to run the tests in this object. It defaults to the list of 
   all non-inherited functions that begin with the word "test".

void setTests(string *tests)
-- Used to override the default test behavior, in order to use
   a certain test function order, use functions that do not
   begin with "test", or use a subset of test functions.

object *suite()
-- Returns an array of test case objects to call. This defaults
   to the current object, but this may be overridden to return
   other cloned test objects in order to collect a number of
   separate test cases objects into a single convenient test case.

mixed run(string test)
-- Called by the test runner. Runs a particular test function in
   the object, and returns either 0 for success, or an error
   message for failure.

void assertTrue(string msg, mixed bool)
-- Asserts that the value 'bool' is true. If not, an error is
   raised, causing the test to fail. The error will contain the
   text in 'msg'.

void assertFalse(string msg, mixed bool)
-- Asserts that the value 'bool' is false. If not, an error is
   raised, causing the test to fail. The error will contain the
   text in 'msg'.

void assertNull(string msg, mixed thing)
-- Asserts that the value 'thing' is null. If not, an error is
   raised, causing the test to fail. The error will contain the
   text in 'msg'. In LPC, this is the same as assertFalse.

void assertEquals(string msg, mixed expecting, mixed actual)
-- Asserts that the value 'actual' is the same as 'expecting'. 
   If not, an error is raised, causing the test to fail. The
   error will contain the text in 'msg'.

void assertNonEmpty(string msg, mixed thing)
-- Asserts that the value 'thing' is nonempty. For mappings, this
   means that the mapping is not ([ ]). For arrays, this means
   that the array is not ({ }). For strings, this means that the
   string is not "". For any other value (object, numeric) this
   means that the value is not 0. If not, an error is raised,
   causing the test to fail. The error will contain the text in
   'msg'.

void assertNonEmpty(string msg, mixed thing)
-- This asserts the opposite of assertNonEmpty; ie. mappings and
   arrays must have at least one element, strings must be of
   length >= 1, and objects/numbers must not be 0.

void fail(string msg)
-- Causes an instant test failure, sending 'msg' in the error
   message.


Examples
-------

Please see /inherits/events_test.c

You can run the example with "rtest /inherits/events_test".

As an example of the use of suite():

object *suite()
{
  object subtest;

  // This sets up a copy of npcbehavetest that only
  // runs two test functions
  subtest = clone_object("/inherits/npcbehavetest");
  subtest->setTests( ({ "test1", "test2" }) );

  return ({ clone_object("/secure/livingtest"),
            clone_object("/secure/monstertest"),
            clone_object("/secure/playertest"),
            clone_object("/inherits/npctest"),
            subtest });
}

If you were to run 'rtest' on this test object, it would run
the livingtest, monstertest, playertest, and subset of npctest.

Note that these tests do not exist as of this writing. :-)


